Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

In general looks great.

One thought that occurred when reviewing this patch is that we have a number of places where we are using

  log.debug(msg % params)

where we probably should be using

  log.debug(msg, params)

for better performance. But I think that is a separate concern so I don't think its a problem with this patch.

The only reason why I'm a +1 and not a +2 is that this patch does make minor changes to previous migrations. The changes seem correct (and preserve functional equivalence) but I'm curious if they're really necessary.

See http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-October/017997.html for more details.

Patch Set 2:

FWIW, I don't think this patch needs to address changing from
  msg = _(...) % params
  log.info(msg)
to
  msg = _(...)
  log.info(msg, params)
although I do prefer the second approach when the formatted message is not going to be reused.


Two questions that have come up from further review, however. First, is there any hacking check we can turn on to ensure we don't accidentally start using locals() again? Second, I noticed some places where the message changes from something like
  msg = _("Some message and %(blah)s")
to
  msg = _("Some message and %s")

While the change matches our style guidelines, I'm curious if we are creating a bunch of translation work that we don't need to? Would it save work for downstream translators if we kept the named substitution in these cases?

Thanks!

Hi Mark, 

Thanks for the prompt reviews.

As far as the creation of new strings, I think you are right. I can revert those in the next PS.

Thank you,

Patch Set 2: (11 inline comments)

Thanks for pointing out that Mark, I noted down the places where it formatting could be avoided at the string level and passed down to the logger.

Also, some interesting points can be seen here http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5082452/python-string-formatting-vs-format. Firstly, the style 

"str %s" % var can cause type errors on tuples. And down near the bottom (3rd last comment as of 2013-11-11) they ask to use advanced string (beneficial while switching to python 3 as well)

As Mark says, these changes are not necessary. (So don't have a -1) However, if we include certain changes to this patch we might as well include as per some of the observations above.

BTW, I think I will need to add the #noqa line might need to be added to the migration files since we won't remove the locals() in those
